Siva Bulusu

14/12/2019

Sales of souvenir data has been provided in the fancy.dat files.It contains monthly sales for a souvenir shop at a beach resort town in Queensland, Australia, for January 1987-December 1993.We are going to predict the sales for next 5 years.

Read the dataset and view it.

souvenir.data <- read.table("fancy-1.txt", header = FALSE, sep="", as.is=TRUE)
View(souvenir.data)

There are 84 values. As per given inputs the data is from January 1987 to December 1993. 7 years in total. That is 7*12 = 84 months. So missing values are not there which is good.

Check the structure of given data.

The data given is not in time series format. So we need to convert the data in to time series.

Convert the data frame into time series and check the format.

souvenir.data.ts <- ts(souvenir.data,start = c(1987,1),end = c(1993,12),frequency = 12)
class(souvenir.data.ts)
## [1] "ts"

Check for stationarity in the given time series.

ADF Test Null Hypothesis(H0): The series has a unit root (value of a =1) Alternate Hypothesis(H1): The series has no unit root.

KPSS Test Null Hypothesis(H0): The data is stationary. Alternate Hypothesis(H1): The data is not stationary.

adf.test(souvenir.data.ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  souvenir.data.ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.0809, Lag order = 4, p-value = 0.5427
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
kpss.test(souvenir.data.ts)
## Warning in kpss.test(souvenir.data.ts): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  souvenir.data.ts

Based on the p-value in both the tests the given data is non-stationary.
